message.content:
Explanation:

- I inspected app/Http/Controllers/CommentController.php. The destroy method:
  - calls $this->authorize('delete', $comment); which can trigger an authorization failure (403) if the authenticated user is not allowed to delete the comment.
  - calls $comment->delete(); to remove the resource.
  - returns response()->turboStream([...]) — this produces an HTML Turbo Streams response (MIME type text/vnd.turbo-stream.html) containing one or more <turbo-stream> fragments (here: remove the comment fragment and update the comments_count fragment). For a successful web DELETE on /comments/{comment} this controller returns a 200 OK with turbo-streams HTML content.
- Route configuration (routes/auth.php) shows this controller is used for the web route Route::resource('comments', CommentController::class)->only(['store', 'destroy']); which sits behind auth/verified middleware — so an unauthenticated request will not be allowed (web behavior usually produces a redirect to login), and an authenticated but unauthorized request will be forbidden (403).
- Model binding for Comment means a non-existent comment will produce a 404 Not Found.

Based on the controller and routing, the likely HTTP responses for DELETE /comments/{comment} handled by this controller are:
- 200 OK with text/vnd.turbo-stream.html body containing <turbo-stream> fragments.
- 401 Unauthorized / redirect to login when unauthenticated (documented here as 401 for API-style docs; web behavior is a redirect).
- 403 Forbidden when authorization fails.
- 404 Not Found when the comment cannot be found.

